f economic progress in Somerset, Maryland's poorest county, can best be explained by factoring history, culture, and social relations into the investigator's research. In this second edition she discusses changes that have taken place in the county since the early 1990s, including the dramatic legal victory of the "Somerset Six" and the Maryland ACLU, which ultimately paved the way for the election of an African American to a top county position for the first time in history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCommunity development -- Maryland -- Somerset County. 0aCommunity developmentzMarylandzSomerset County. 0aEconomic development -- Social aspects -- Maryland -- Somerset County. 0aEconomic developmentxSocial aspectszMarylandzSomerset County. 0aSocial action -- Maryland -- Somerset County. 0aSocial actionzMarylandzSomerset County. 4aBusiness and Economics : Development. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPublic Policy : Public Administration. 4aSociology : Rural Sociology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Regional Planning.2bisacsh1 aHall, Kirkland J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438448886423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438448886/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles